00:13:24.700 --> 00:13:25.200
No.

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:27.610
The first rule of queer
club is that everyone's

00:13:27.610 --> 00:13:29.440
in charge of their
own labels, OK?

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:31.210
No matter how much
someone else thinks

00:13:31.210 --> 00:13:34.550
you don't fit that
definition, it doesn't matter.

00:13:34.550 --> 00:13:37.750
Because this is how
people live and love.

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:38.940
You can't pin it down.

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:40.145
It is all gray area.

00:13:40.145 --> 00:13:41.520
There is nothing
black and white.

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:43.220
This is all a continuum.

00:13:43.220 --> 00:13:46.440
There is nothing
specific here other

00:13:46.440 --> 00:13:48.610
than people's lived
experiences, and you just

00:13:48.610 --> 00:13:50.027
don't get to argue
with those, OK?

00:13:50.027 --> 00:13:51.901
So everyone is in charge
of their own labels.

00:13:51.901 --> 00:13:54.070
So some people might
identify as transsexual,

00:13:54.070 --> 00:13:56.360
and that is absolutely fine.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:13:57.850
The reason why
people don't like it

00:13:57.850 --> 00:14:00.580
anymore is because
it's quite medically.

00:14:00.580 --> 00:14:04.270
It's such a focus on
the medical aspect

00:14:04.270 --> 00:14:07.100
of being trans, which
doesn't apply to everybody.

00:14:07.100 --> 00:14:11.230
Not everyone wants to medically
transition or even consider

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:13.480
that to be an OK term to use.

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:15.520
So yeah, we don't
really use it anymore.

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:19.360
So go forth and
don't use, please.

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:22.720
And it comes from this idea that
your sex is your gender, right?

00:14:22.720 --> 00:14:25.750
So that's not true.

00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:28.450
Sex and gender are
very separate things.

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:31.120
Sex is a series of
biological traits,

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:33.080
and gender is [MUMBLES].

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:38.260
I don't fully know.

00:14:38.260 --> 00:14:40.840
That's why there's
college departments called

00:14:40.840 --> 00:14:42.100
gender studies.

00:14:42.100 --> 00:14:43.960
I guess they haven't
figured it out.

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:44.650
So I don't know.

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:46.307
Gender is like a
social construct

00:14:46.307 --> 00:14:48.890
that's different from culture
to culture and depending on what

00:14:48.890 --> 00:14:49.515
time you're in.

00:14:49.515 --> 00:14:52.480
But seems to be innate in
most people about the gender

00:14:52.480 --> 00:14:53.250
that they are.

00:14:53.250 --> 00:14:54.490
This is complex.

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:56.450
I can't cover this
all in this workshop.

00:14:56.450 --> 00:14:59.230
But the idea that it's
connected to your sex

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:02.560
is this concept called
bioessentialism.

00:15:02.560 --> 00:15:06.130
And if you're leveling
up, more woke, going up

00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:08.800
the triangle of wokeness,
this is the type of thing

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.270
you can say casually at a party.

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:12.910
You can be like, I'm just
against bioessentialism.

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:13.870
And then leave.

00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:17.715
Just leave straight away.

00:15:17.715 --> 00:15:20.090
You don't want to stay after
you say that in case someone

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:20.923
knows more than you.

00:15:20.923 --> 00:15:22.306
Because this has happened to me.

00:15:22.306 --> 00:15:23.680
Someone's there,
like, an expert.

00:15:23.680 --> 00:15:25.060
And I'm like, oh, shit.

00:15:25.060 --> 00:15:27.030
I just want to sound smart.

00:15:27.030 --> 00:15:29.530
So yeah, bioessentialism
is this idea

00:15:29.530 --> 00:15:32.510
that your biology is essential
to your gender, and it is bad.

00:15:32.510 --> 00:15:35.700
It's not a cool thing.

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:36.370
Right.

00:15:36.370 --> 00:15:37.160
Q.

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:38.080
AUDIENCE: Queer.

00:15:38.080 --> 00:15:38.690
BELLA FITZPATRICK: Yay.

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:40.090
Does anybody feel like
you can't use the word

00:15:40.090 --> 00:15:41.260
"queer" if you're not LGBT?

00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:46.410
A little nod, little
nod, some people?

00:15:46.410 --> 00:15:49.090
But most of you feel like
it's grand to use it?

00:15:49.090 --> 00:15:49.590
Cool.

00:15:49.590 --> 00:15:53.680
Well, I speak for
all LGBT people.

00:15:53.680 --> 00:15:54.732
And yeah, it is fine.

00:15:54.732 --> 00:15:55.440
It's fine to use.

00:15:55.440 --> 00:15:58.176
Absolutely.

00:15:58.176 --> 00:15:59.800
Not everyone would
agree with me there.

00:15:59.800 --> 00:16:02.460
Not everyone is going to agree
with everything I say here.

00:16:02.460 --> 00:16:05.340
The reason why it's fine to use
is because it's a descriptor.

00:16:05.340 --> 00:16:06.780
It describes things.

00:16:06.780 --> 00:16:09.369
Yes, it's a pejorative term
reclaimed by a minority group.

00:16:09.369 --> 00:16:11.910
And like other pejorative terms
reclaimed by minority groups,

00:16:11.910 --> 00:16:13.510
you've no business using those.

00:16:13.510 --> 00:16:17.929
But this one, you do, because it
is a way to be more inclusive.

00:16:17.929 --> 00:16:20.220
So rather than saying "gay"
as a collective term, which

00:16:20.220 --> 00:16:22.950
is not OK, you say "queer"
as a collective term.

00:16:22.950 --> 00:16:24.750
So I'm bisexual.

00:16:24.750 --> 00:16:26.910
And therefore, if you
were to say later,

00:16:26.910 --> 00:16:29.520
I had a talk by a gay
woman about gay issues,

00:16:29.520 --> 00:16:30.555
that would not be true.

00:16:30.555 --> 00:16:31.680
None of that would be true.

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:33.322
It wouldn't make
any sense to say.

00:16:33.322 --> 00:16:35.280
But you could say I had
a talk by a queer woman

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:37.470
about queer issues.

00:16:37.470 --> 00:16:40.890
Queerness is what connects
everybody in the community.

00:16:40.890 --> 00:16:43.320
Not everyone identifies that
way, because rule number one,

00:16:43.320 --> 00:16:45.028
everyone's in charge
of their own labels.

00:16:45.028 --> 00:16:48.240
But most people do of
the younger generation,

00:16:48.240 --> 00:16:50.970
and most people we talk to in
schools do identify that way.

00:16:50.970 --> 00:16:55.262
So say I'm a bisexual
woman, Julian's a gay man,

00:16:55.262 --> 00:16:56.970
but what connects us
is we're both queer.

00:16:56.970 --> 00:16:57.470
Yeah.

00:16:57.470 --> 00:16:59.850
That's like, the
multiple Venn diagram

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:02.470
of all these identities,
the very middle bit--

00:17:02.470 --> 00:17:03.600
that's queer.

00:17:03.600 --> 00:17:06.970
So yeah, go forth
and use if you want.

00:17:06.970 --> 00:17:08.068
I?

00:17:08.068 --> 00:17:08.859
AUDIENCE: Intersex.

00:17:08.859 --> 00:17:09.520
BELLA FITZPATRICK: Intersex.

00:17:09.520 --> 00:17:10.450
Very good, yeah.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:14.288
So this is where we don't
love exact definitions.

00:17:14.288 --> 00:17:16.329
But I guess with intersex,
it can be quite handy.

00:17:16.329 --> 00:17:18.430
So it's having sexual
characteristics

00:17:18.430 --> 00:17:22.280
not typically associated with
being either male or female.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.510
So this is where lots
of people think of sex

00:17:25.510 --> 00:17:27.190
as being a binary concept--

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:30.070
men over here, women over here--

00:17:30.070 --> 00:17:33.610
penises, vaginas--
nothing in the middle.

00:17:33.610 --> 00:17:36.050
All penises in one
box, and all vaginas--

00:17:36.050 --> 00:17:38.610
oh, sorry.

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:39.742
That was gross, sorry.

00:17:42.340 --> 00:17:44.290
Yeah, and there is
space in between.

00:17:44.290 --> 00:17:47.710
There is different
ways to have biology.

00:17:47.710 --> 00:17:51.370
And they don't fall into a
certain pattern all the time.

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:54.200
And if that's the way you
are, then you're intersex.

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:55.660
And it's not a birth defect.

00:17:55.660 --> 00:17:57.077
It's not an abnormality.

00:17:57.077 --> 00:17:58.660
It's the way skin
color and hair color

00:17:58.660 --> 00:18:01.700
vary between individuals, so
do characteristics of sex.

00:18:01.700 --> 00:18:03.190
So this would also
be an argument

00:18:03.190 --> 00:18:05.560
against bioessentialism.

00:18:05.560 --> 00:18:07.450
So that's really good to know.

00:18:07.450 --> 00:18:09.610
Just back on queer for a second.

00:18:09.610 --> 00:18:11.410
When I said that
it's more inclusive,

00:18:11.410 --> 00:18:15.850
that allows you to sidestep
an issue called gaywashing.

00:18:15.850 --> 00:18:17.480
This is where a
