00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:39.200
So pansexual is a
brilliant term for people

00:21:39.200 --> 00:21:42.550
who feel it reflects
them better than bisexual

00:21:42.550 --> 00:21:45.305
because there is a common
misconception that bisexuality

00:21:45.305 --> 00:21:47.180
means that you're
attracted to men and women.

00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:49.550
I'm sure that's probably
what you thought bisexual

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:51.450
was on your way in here today.

00:21:51.450 --> 00:21:52.160
It's not.

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:54.070
It hasn't meant that
in a long, long time.

00:21:54.070 --> 00:21:57.334
So "bisexual" was coined in
1873 or something like that.

00:21:57.334 --> 00:21:59.250
And of course, that's
what it meant back then.

00:21:59.250 --> 00:22:01.080
But for a long time,
the bisexual community

00:22:01.080 --> 00:22:03.470
is considered the
binary aspect of it,

00:22:03.470 --> 00:22:06.530
linguistically, to mean your
own gender and other genders.

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:09.830
So I'm attracted to women
and people of other genders.

00:22:09.830 --> 00:22:15.240
So it's inclusive of the many
genders we have in the world.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:18.222
But because most
people don't know that,

00:22:18.222 --> 00:22:20.180
you might be uncomfortable
identifying that way

00:22:20.180 --> 00:22:22.640
and having people misconstrue
what you mean by that.

00:22:22.640 --> 00:22:26.150
So pansexual is a
great way to reject

00:22:26.150 --> 00:22:28.310
gender binaryism-- this
idea that there's only

00:22:28.310 --> 00:22:29.090
men and women.

00:22:29.090 --> 00:22:31.580
That's another term
for the party, right?

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:34.770
I just reject gender
binaryism-- and then leave.

00:22:34.770 --> 00:22:37.920
The leaving is important.

00:22:37.920 --> 00:22:40.060
And pansexual-- because
"pan" means all, right?

00:22:40.060 --> 00:22:43.340
"Bi" means two, "pan"
means all-- like panorama.

00:22:43.340 --> 00:22:44.650
All of the rama.

00:22:44.650 --> 00:22:48.330
I just don't know, don't
know what that means.

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:50.630
So it's kind of a newer term.

00:22:50.630 --> 00:22:54.089
If you take Google Trends that
kind of came up in around 2007.

00:22:54.089 --> 00:22:56.255
There's a lot of overlap
between the two identities.

00:22:56.255 --> 00:22:57.713
So one way you
could think about it

00:22:57.713 --> 00:23:02.180
is that pan people are gender
blind when it comes to picking

00:23:02.180 --> 00:23:04.700
a sexual or romantic partner.

00:23:04.700 --> 00:23:07.450
But there's no animosity
between the two groups.

00:23:07.450 --> 00:23:08.240
We're friends.

00:23:08.240 --> 00:23:10.991
No dance-offs or
anything like that.

00:23:10.991 --> 00:23:11.490
All right.

00:23:11.490 --> 00:23:12.160
And plus?

00:23:12.160 --> 00:23:13.660
AUDIENCE: [? Anything ?]
[? else. ?]

00:23:13.660 --> 00:23:15.035
BELLA FITZPATRICK:
Anything else.

00:23:15.035 --> 00:23:15.910
Absolutely, yeah.

00:23:15.910 --> 00:23:18.250
Could not possibly cover it all.

00:23:18.250 --> 00:23:19.960
Anything else-- a lot
of other identities

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:23.950
fall under these
umbrella identities here.

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:26.860
So, say, genderfluidity
or nonbinary-- most people

00:23:26.860 --> 00:23:28.660
consider that to
fall under trans.

00:23:28.660 --> 00:23:31.880
Because trans simply means that
you were assigned incorrectly

00:23:31.880 --> 00:23:32.380
at birth.

00:23:32.380 --> 00:23:33.950
That's what it means.

00:23:33.950 --> 00:23:36.836
It's not about being in the
wrong body, nothing like that.

00:23:36.836 --> 00:23:38.710
Try to steer away from
that type of rhetoric.

00:23:38.710 --> 00:23:40.880
It means you were assigned
incorrectly at birth.

00:23:40.880 --> 00:23:44.110
So what I mean is, you
got born, remember?

00:23:44.110 --> 00:23:49.270
And a midwife looks at you
or a doctor looks at you

00:23:49.270 --> 00:23:52.060
and decides on your
external genitalia

00:23:52.060 --> 00:23:53.590
whether you're a boy or girl.

00:23:53.590 --> 00:23:56.740
And this works out just really
well for a lot of people,

00:23:56.740 --> 00:23:59.440
like 98% of people,
this works out well

00:23:59.440 --> 00:24:01.580
because they also identify
with that same way.

00:24:01.580 --> 00:24:05.492
And they feel comfortable within
that role that's in society.

00:24:05.492 --> 00:24:07.450
Or they might not feel
comfortable in the role,

00:24:07.450 --> 00:24:09.260
but they still
identify that way.

00:24:09.260 --> 00:24:12.169
And this is called
being cisgender, OK?

00:24:12.169 --> 00:24:13.960
So if you were assigned
correctly at birth,

00:24:13.960 --> 00:24:15.460
you're cisgender.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:17.890
Comes from Latin, means
"on the same side."

00:24:17.890 --> 00:24:19.450
So "cis" means "on
the same side."

00:24:19.450 --> 00:24:21.070
"Trans" means "on
the other side."

00:24:21.070 --> 00:24:22.760
So you know trans fats?

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:23.260
Yeah.

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:26.320
That's when the hydrogen atom's
on the other side of the carbon

00:24:26.320 --> 00:24:27.190
chain.

00:24:27.190 --> 00:24:30.510
That's the only time I
use my chemistry degree--

00:24:30.510 --> 00:24:32.990
four years for that sentence.

00:24:32.990 --> 00:24:35.470
So yeah, if you were
assigned correctly at birth,

00:24:35.470 --> 00:24:36.310
you were cisgender.

00:24:36.310 --> 00:24:37.570
If you were assigned
incorrectly at birth,

00:24:37.570 --> 00:24:39.010
you were transgender, OK?

00:24:39.010 --> 00:24:43.030
So for every word of
something in the community,

00:24:43.030 --> 00:24:45.070
there's a word for
everything that's not that.

00:24:45.070 --> 00:24:47.790
And that just allows us to
use more appropriate language

00:24:47.790 --> 00:24:49.780
than saying normal or
something like that,

00:24:49.780 --> 00:24:51.659
which would not be as ideal.

00:24:51.659 --> 00:24:53.200
But as I say, it's
very front-loaded.

00:24:53.200 --> 00:24:54.640
So there are other options.

00:24:54.640 --> 00:24:58.520
So QUILTBAG-- yeah?

00:24:58.520 --> 00:25:00.290
It's another acronym.

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:03.290
It's also the name of
my knitting circle.

00:25:03.290 --> 00:25:03.840
OK.

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:06.810
So I think we've done
all of these letters

00:25:06.810 --> 00:25:10.372
except for U. Anybody
know what U is?

00:25:10.372 --> 00:25:11.330
AUDIENCE: [? Unsure? ?]

00:25:11.330 --> 00:25:11.790
BELLA FITZPATRICK: Yeah.

00:25:11.790 --> 00:25:12.240
Unsure.

00:25:12.240 --> 00:25:12.823
Yeah, exactly.

00:25:12.823 --> 00:25:14.050
Undecided.

00:25:14.050 --> 00:25:17.470
Yeah, curious, that type of
thing-- unsure, undecided.

00:25:17.470 --> 00:25:19.470
This just allows us to
think about these letters

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:20.310
in a different way.

00:25:20.310 --> 00:25:22.720
Because linguistics
is really important.

00:25:22.720 --> 00:25:24.930
And the fact that we
front-load LGBT all the time

00:25:24.930 --> 00:25:27.221
does actually impact how you
think about the community.

00:25:27.221 --> 00:25:29.190
So if you just mix it
up, that's really great.

00:25:29.190 --> 00:25:31.110
There are other ways,
as well, though.

00:25:31.110 --> 00:25:32.690
MOGAI.

00:25:32.690 --> 00:25:33.190
All right.

00:25:33.190 --> 00:25:34.398
Let's see what you know here.

00:25:34.398 --> 00:25:35.262
M?

00:25:35.262 --> 00:25:36.890
I'm only joking.

00:25:36.890 --> 00:25:38.190
You wouldn't know it.

00:25:38.190 --> 00:25:41.040
So it stands for
Marginalized Orientations,

00:25:41.040 --> 00:25:43.510
Gender Alignments,
and Intersex people.

00:25:43.510 --> 00:25:44.010
OK.

00:25:44.010 --> 00:25:47.010
Marginalized orientations,
gender alignments,

00:25:47.010 --> 00:25:48.750
and intersex people.

00:25:48.750 --> 00:25:52.820
So marginalized orientations are
not heterosexual orientations.

00:25:52.820 --> 00:25:54.240
Marginalized gender
alignments are

00:25:54.240 --> 00:25:57.810
when you're gender assigned
at birth does not correspond

00:25:57.810 --> 00:25:58.980
to who you actually are.

00:25:58.980 --> 00:26:00.749
And intersex people
are intersex people.

00:26:00.749 --> 00:26:02.790
So it's kind of is a nice
way to cover everybody.

00:26:02.790 --> 00:26:04.830
That make sense?

00:26:04.830 --> 00:26:06.750
Another one for
the party, right?

00:26:06.750 --> 00:26:07.401
Yes?

00:26:07.401 --> 00:26:08.907
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:08.907 --> 00:26:10.490
BELLA FITZPATRICK:
Beautiful question.

00:26:10.490 --> 00:26:13.160
Really good question about--
people say this a lot,

00:26:13.160 --> 00:26:15.250
being gay is not the same
thing as being trans.

00:26:15.250 --> 00:26:17.030
Yeah, OK.

00:26:17.030 --> 00:26:20.810
Why we do this is because
all of the LGBT community

00:26:20.810 --> 00:26:24.830
fall under not the
assumption of the norm.

00:26:24.830 --> 00:26:26.810
That is what binds us.

00:26:26.810 --> 00:26:29.900
So when you're born, you get
assigned a label at birth.

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:32.180
People expect you to
identify that way,

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:34.260
and people expect you
to behave that way.

00:26:34.260 --> 00:26:35.801
And part of that
behavior is that you

00:26:35.801 --> 00:26:37.340
will like the opposite sex, OK?

00:26:37.340 --> 00:26:41.090
So this all falls under a
line of assumed identities,

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:44.180
of all of which the
LGBT community are not.

00:26:44.180 --> 00:26:46.790
There is unbelievable
similar experiences

00:26:46.790 --> 00:26:51.500
between people who are LGB
and people who are TQIAP.

00:26:51.500 --> 00:26:53.210
It's also about autonomy, right?

00:26:53.210 --> 00:26:57.080
Right to self-identify, right
to decide your own labels--

00:26:57.080 --> 00:26:59.090
and we all struggle under that.

00:26:59.090 --> 00:27:02.060
So we are all united
by this otherness,

00:27:02.060 --> 00:27:04.370
this marginalization.

00:27:04.370 --> 00:27:08.960
And the LGBT rights movement was
started by trans women of color

00:27:08.960 --> 00:27:10.500
who were sex workers.

00:27:10.500 --> 00:27:12.230
And that's a really
important point.

00:27:12.230 --> 00:27:15.680
At no point was T
tacked on anywhere.

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:18.980
Maybe in the
marketing department,

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:21.800
who I've yet to meet,
of the LGBT community--

00:27:21.800 --> 00:27:23.390
I need to have a chat with them.

00:27:23.390 --> 00:27:27.140
But at no point did
it get tacked on.

00:27:27.140 --> 00:27:29.420
It was always the one community.

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:32.150
Because for a long
time, it was so taboo.

00:27:32.150 --> 00:27:34.400
And it would just mean
your instant death

00:27:34.400 --> 00:27:36.380
if you came out as trans.

00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:39.260
So that's where you have
ideas around drag culture

00:27:39.260 --> 00:27:42.500
where there's a lot of drag
queens were actually trans.

00:27:42.500 --> 00:27:44.990
Now we can think about them
as very separate identities.

00:27:44.990 --> 00:27:46.880
But at the beginning,
that was always

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:49.220
in the gay bars, that was
always with the lesbians,

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:51.590
that was always with the bi
people, the queer people,

00:27:51.590 --> 00:27:54.020
the people who didn't get to
decide how they were assigned

00:27:54.020 --> 00:27:55.670
at birth, because
they had genitalia

00:27:55.670 --> 00:27:58.370
that looked like none of
the above options, which

00:27:58.370 --> 00:27:59.580
is male or female.

00:27:59.580 --> 00:28:01.700
And they had unnecessary
cosmetic surgery

00:28:01.700 --> 00:28:03.470
done on them as babies.

00:28:03.470 --> 00:28:05.540
And that falls under
the line of not

00:28:05.540 --> 00:28:07.760
being allowed to
identify yourself

00:28:07.760 --> 00:28:09.320
and not having the autonomy.

00:28:09.320 --> 00:28:12.926
So what connects us
all is this experience.

00:28:12.926 --> 00:28:14.300
We are all connected
in this way.

00:28:14.300 --> 00:28:14.800
Yes.

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:16.440
We have different experiences.

00:28:16.440 --> 00:28:18.821
I have a different experience
from a trans woman.

00:28:18.821 --> 00:28:21.070
I have a different experience
from an intersex person.

00:28:21.070 --> 00:28:23.810
I have a different experience
from an asexual person.

00:28:23.810 --> 00:28:27.230
But I have more similar
experiences with them

00:28:27.230 --> 00:28:29.210
than I do with cis,
straight people.

00:28:29.210 --> 00:28:32.260
So hopefully that
answers a little bit.

00:28:32.260 --> 00:28:32.810
OK.

00:28:32.810 --> 00:28:35.480
So this is what we're trying
to get people to care about.

00:28:35.480 --> 00:28:38.240
And there's a few principles.

00:28:38.240 --> 00:28:40.220
Learning is easier
than unlearning.

00:28:40.220 --> 00:28:42.980
OK, so learning
something from nothing

00:28:42.980 --> 00:28:45.680
is way easier than undoing
social conditioning, which is

00:28:45.680 --> 00:28:47.240
what we have to do in ShoutOut.

00:28:47.240 --> 00:28:49.770
You can't be right,
but you can be wrong.

00:28:49.770 --> 00:28:53.197
This is the shit,
but this is true.

00:28:53.197 --> 00:28:55.280
Not everything I've said
here today will be right.

00:28:55.280 --> 00:28:57.920
It has been updated
since we walked in.

00:28:57.920 --> 00:28:59.600
We are constantly evolving.

00:28:59.600 --> 00:29:01.290
And again, it's all gray area.

00:29:01.290 --> 00:29:03.509
So you can't be right
about your definitions.

00:29:03.509 --> 00:29:06.050
You can't be right about your
understanding of other people's

00:29:06.050 --> 00:29:07.260
experiences.

00:29:07.260 --> 00:29:09.260
But you can be super wrong.

00:29:09.260 --> 00:29:11.870
You could say it in the wrong
way that really excludes

00:29:11.870 --> 00:29:15.380
a lot of people, or you can
say it in the most updated way.

00:29:15.380 --> 00:29:16.942
But you're never right, OK?

00:29:16.942 --> 00:29:17.900
Just bear that in mind.

00:29:17.900 --> 00:29:19.160
I'm not right right now.

00:29:19.160 --> 00:29:20.540
No one's right.

00:29:20.540 --> 00:29:22.649
You can only be right
about your own experiences.

00:29:22.649 --> 00:29:24.440
And then knowing is
not the same as caring.

00:29:24.440 --> 00:29:27.770
And this is key, OK?

00:29:27.770 --> 00:29:31.940
Being an ally is not about
knowing your LGBTQIAs

00:29:31.940 --> 00:29:35.420
from your MOGAIs,
your trans demi guys

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:37.880
from your asexual
heteroromantics.

00:29:37.880 --> 00:29:39.390
It's not about that.

00:29:39.390 --> 00:29:41.600
It's about not making
assumptions and taking people's

00:29:41.600 --> 00:29:44.480
life experiences at face value.

00:29:44.480 --> 00:29:46.640
But we have to come
up with different ways

00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:48.360
to teach our
different audiences.

00:29:48.360 --> 00:29:51.860
So we have our
student workshops.

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:53.870
We have our teachers,
parents, guardians, youth

00:29:53.870 --> 00:29:54.740
workers workshops.

00:29:54.740 --> 00:29:56.404
And we have other adults--

00:29:56.404 --> 00:29:57.320
you are other adults--

00:29:57.320 --> 00:29:58.820
corporates, right?

00:29:58.820 --> 00:30:02.270
Other adults-- something
like medical professionals

00:30:02.270 --> 00:30:03.860
are other adults--
that type of thing.

00:30:03.860 --> 00:30:06.480
And we have a different
tactic for each one.

00:30:06.480 --> 00:30:09.650
This is basically manipulation.

00:30:09.650 --> 00:30:11.660
Different forms.

00:30:11.660 --> 00:30:14.240
So in the student workshop,
we use social norm theorem.

00:30:14.240 --> 00:30:16.070
This is where you
present a change

00:30:16.070 --> 00:30:19.070
that you want to see as
having already happened.

00:30:19.070 --> 00:30:21.410
It's used in the States
a lot for things like--

00:30:21.410 --> 00:30:23.060
they'll have signs
up in college being

00:30:23.060 --> 00:30:25.040
like, "80% of people
who go out drinking

00:30:25.040 --> 00:30:26.420
have a big meal beforehand."

00:30:26.420 --> 00:30:28.200
And that's just not true, right?

00:30:28.200 --> 00:30:30.700
But then people are like, oh,
that's the normal thing to do.

00:30:30.700 --> 00:30:31.700
I'll do that.

00:30:31.700 --> 00:30:33.710
So we kind of present
LGBT acceptance

00:30:33.710 --> 00:30:36.770
as being the norm, that
if you want to get on well

00:30:36.770 --> 00:30:38.810
in your workplace,
you should try

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:42.380
to be accepting and celebratory
of other identities,

00:30:42.380 --> 00:30:47.390
be they LGBT or otherwise,
and that this has happened.

00:30:47.390 --> 00:30:48.230
It is lies.

00:30:48.230 --> 00:30:51.200
But look, there you go.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:53.960
So our workshop with students,
because we go into schools

00:30:53.960 --> 00:30:57.370
and we're not teachers,
we have to, first of all,

00:30:57.370 --> 00:30:58.430
authoritize ourselves.

00:30:58.430 --> 00:31:01.290
I actually don't think
that's a word, but look.

00:31:01.290 --> 00:31:04.550
And we do that by creating
a contract just up

00:31:04.550 --> 00:31:06.320
on the whiteboard in school.

00:31:06.320 --> 00:31:09.530
And we say, can we all
agree that we'll be sound,

00:31:09.530 --> 00:31:12.272
that we'll be confidential
if anybody says anything,

00:31:12.272 --> 00:31:13.730
and that we don't
talk out of turn?

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:16.210
And that just kind of puts
you in a authoritative stance.

00:31:16.210 --> 00:31:17.420
And then you have
to humanize yourself

00:31:17.420 --> 00:31:19.003
by giving your own
personal coming out

00:31:19.003 --> 00:31:22.670
story or your personal story
on your journey as an ally.

00:31:22.670 --> 00:31:25.760
Then we educate them by telling
them the definitions for LGBT.

00:31:25.760 --> 00:31:28.682
We get them to practice their
empathy by putting themselves

00:31:28.682 --> 00:31:30.890
in the idea of other people's
shoes or other people's

00:31:30.890 --> 00:31:31.490
positions.

00:31:31.490 --> 00:31:33.512
We put that into practice
in scenario groups.

00:31:33.512 --> 00:31:35.720
So we put them into groups
and decide, what would you

00:31:35.720 --> 00:31:36.590
do if your friend came out?

00:31:36.590 --> 00:31:38.480
What would you do if
you witnessed bullying?

00:31:38.480 --> 00:31:41.510
And then we empower them
by letting them come up

00:31:41.510 --> 00:31:43.100
with the next agenda
for how they're

00:31:43.100 --> 00:31:45.300
going to make their school
an LGBT-inclusive place.

00:31:45.300 --> 00:31:46.640
And this is key--

00:31:46.640 --> 00:31:47.869
so important.

00:31:47.869 --> 00:31:49.910
This is really important
that kids feel ownership

00:31:49.910 --> 00:31:51.110
over the culture
of their school.

00:31:51.110 --> 00:31:53.240
The school is not four
walls that they walk into.

00:31:53.240 --> 00:31:54.470
They are the school.

00:31:54.470 --> 00:31:56.060
And even if it's
just in their class

00:31:56.060 --> 00:31:57.800
or their group of
friends, they can

00:31:57.800 --> 00:31:59.900
make an LGBT-inclusive bubble.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:01.791
And they have the
power to do that.

00:32:01.791 --> 00:32:03.290
So this is a really
important point.

00:32:03.290 --> 00:32:05.577
Any suggestions they make,
we feedback to the school.

00:32:05.577 --> 00:32:07.910
And this is where we find out
a lot of troubling things,

00:32:07.910 --> 00:32:09.530
such as kids not
being able to bring

00:32:09.530 --> 00:32:12.230
same-sex dates to
the dance, girls

00:32:12.230 --> 00:32:14.727
not being able to have hair
shorter than their shoulder,

00:32:14.727 --> 00:32:17.060
trans kids being forced to
wear the uniform that they're

00:32:17.060 --> 00:32:17.819
uncomfortable in.

00:32:17.819 --> 00:32:19.610
And we get to feed that
back to the schools

00:32:19.610 --> 00:32:21.780
and hopefully see some change.

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:24.590
Then with teachers, parents,
guardians, and youth workers,

00:32:24.590 --> 00:32:26.570
gently does it, OK?

00:32:26.570 --> 00:32:29.660
They already care a shit ton.

00:32:29.660 --> 00:32:32.850
That is the technical term.

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:35.570
They are there because
they care so, so much.

00:32:35.570 --> 00:32:39.020
I have never really had to
get a teacher on-site caring

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:40.710
about the well-being
of their students,

00:32:40.710 --> 00:32:43.210
even if they disagree with me,
even if they think everything

00:32:43.210 --> 00:32:46.550
I say is liberal hogwash,
they still really care.

00:32:46.550 --> 00:32:48.400
And if you keep on
bringing it back to,

00:32:48.400 --> 00:32:52.190
oh, our only goal here is
kids not killing themselves,

00:32:52.190 --> 00:32:54.590
then they get on board
with you pretty quickly,

00:32:54.590 --> 00:32:58.340
even if they don't agree with
the methods you've suggested.

00:32:58.340 --> 00:33:00.200
So we like to reassure them.

00:33:00.200 --> 00:33:01.130
This is solvable.

00:33:01.130 --> 00:33:04.280
These are solvable problems--
a few steps, you'll be grand.

00:33:04.280 --> 00:33:06.230
Educate them, put
it in practice,

00:33:06.230 --> 00:33:07.940
and empower them to
go forward-- so kind

00:33:07.940 --> 00:33:10.220
of similar to the student
workshop in a lot of ways.

00:33:10.220 --> 00:33:11.870
And then other adults--

00:33:11.870 --> 00:33:13.280
different, right?

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:17.670
We use intellectualization to
make you value the concepts,

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:18.170
OK?

00:33:18.170 --> 00:33:19.046
That's the idea here.

00:33:19.046 --> 00:33:21.378
Because most of the time,
when we're doing other adults,

00:33:21.378 --> 00:33:22.550
we're doing corporates.

00:33:22.550 --> 00:33:24.680
Most people who work in
corporates go to college.

00:33:24.680 --> 00:33:27.980
We have a value system
around higher ideas,

00:33:27.980 --> 00:33:29.867
and we just exploit
that by making

00:33:29.867 --> 00:33:32.450
it seem like a difficult thing
to get your head around so then

00:33:32.450 --> 00:33:33.830
you will value it.

00:33:33.830 --> 00:33:35.630
The main issue we
have with corporates

00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:37.940
is that people come
to seminars and think,

00:33:37.940 --> 00:33:40.550
I am going to be
patronized by someone

00:33:40.550 --> 00:33:42.620
who's going to tell me
to be nice to gay people.

00:33:42.620 --> 00:33:44.360
And I know to be
nice to gay people.

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:46.520
So we need to make sure
that they know that it

00:33:46.520 --> 00:33:47.790
is more in-depth than that.

00:33:47.790 --> 00:33:48.690
They are going to
learn something.

00:33:48.690 --> 00:33:49.940
It is going to be interesting.

00:33:49.940 --> 00:33:53.430
They are going to be able to
use it at a party and walk away.

00:33:53.430 --> 00:33:56.570
So the first thing we need
to do is horrify them, OK?

00:33:56.570 --> 00:33:57.800
This is the first step--

00:33:57.800 --> 00:33:59.294
get them to care.

00:33:59.294 --> 00:34:00.710
And that's where
we bring in stats

00:34:00.710 --> 00:34:04.700
like three times more attempted
suicide by LGBT young people

00:34:04.700 --> 00:34:07.760
compared to their cis,
straight counterparts, twice

00:34:07.760 --> 00:34:11.810
as much self-harm, and four
times the amount of depression,

00:34:11.810 --> 00:34:14.210
stress, and anxiety.

00:34:14.210 --> 00:34:15.080
Get them to care.

00:34:15.080 --> 00:34:17.150
Get them to realize,
post-marriage equality,

00:34:17.150 --> 00:34:18.777
we have not solved everything.

00:34:18.777 --> 00:34:19.610
Then we soothe them.

00:34:19.610 --> 00:34:20.159
It's OK.

00:34:20.159 --> 00:34:21.810
It's OK, corporates.

00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:25.010
It'll be all right.

00:34:25.010 --> 00:34:26.431
That, there are
things we can do.

00:34:26.431 --> 00:34:27.389
There's an action plan.

00:34:27.389 --> 00:34:28.310
There's an agenda.

00:34:28.310 --> 00:34:29.969
It'll be fine.

00:34:29.969 --> 00:34:31.760
Then we engaged them
with complex theories.

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:33.350
Bamboozle them.

00:34:33.350 --> 00:34:36.540
And then we horrify them
again so they leave,

00:34:36.540 --> 00:34:37.790
and they want to do something.

00:34:37.790 --> 00:34:41.659
That's when we talk about the
unnecessary "normalization"

00:34:41.659 --> 00:34:43.909
surgeries done on intersex
young people, which

00:34:43.909 --> 00:34:46.909
is the next big thing for the
LGBT community in Ireland,

00:34:46.909 --> 00:34:47.750
just to stop these.

00:34:47.750 --> 00:34:50.460
And they have been stopped
in other countries.

00:34:50.460 --> 00:34:52.783
This is very behind
the curtain, guys.

00:34:52.783 --> 00:34:55.199
I feel a little uncomfortable
that you know all my tactics

00:34:55.199 --> 00:34:56.989
now, but look.

00:34:56.989 --> 00:35:03.120
So how we go about
intellectualizing it is,

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:06.570
rather than explaining
each letter in a definition

00:35:06.570 --> 00:35:09.480
in a silo, we consider
them as falling somewhere

00:35:09.480 --> 00:35:11.810
on a series of spectra, OK?

00:35:11.810 --> 00:35:14.190
And this is really important
because everyone's reflected

00:35:14.190 --> 00:35:16.529
in these, not just LGBT people.

00:35:16.529 --> 00:35:18.570
Straight, cis people are
reflected in these, too.

00:35:18.570 --> 00:35:20.361
And once you can see
yourself in something,

00:35:20.361 --> 00:35:22.710
suddenly, you care about
it a little bit more.

00:35:22.710 --> 00:35:25.094
So I'm not going to go
through the full whack of what

00:35:25.094 --> 00:35:26.760
we do, because it
takes about two hours,

00:35:26.760 --> 00:35:29.130
and the sun is shining,
so I won't do that.

00:35:29.130 --> 00:35:32.860
But this is just a general
idea of what it looks like.

00:35:32.860 --> 00:35:34.950
So we do this on a flip
chart on a white board.

00:35:34.950 --> 00:35:35.790
It's very organic.

00:35:35.790 --> 00:35:37.050
We never really do
it on PowerPoint.

00:35:37.050 --> 00:35:39.175
Because I think there's,
like, a Pavlovian response

00:35:39.175 --> 00:35:41.480
to PowerPoint, which
is to fall asleep.

00:35:41.480 --> 00:35:43.930
So I'm apologizing if
this is happening now.

00:35:43.930 --> 00:35:46.420
But we consider these
spectras like sexuality,

00:35:46.420 --> 00:35:48.850
sexual orientation, gender
expression, gender identity,

00:35:48.850 --> 00:35:50.190
and biological sex--

00:35:50.190 --> 00:35:51.810
all of them fall on a spectra.

00:35:51.810 --> 00:35:54.600
Some of them need to be a
triangle because there's ideas

00:35:54.600 --> 00:35:56.932
outside our binary concepts.

00:35:56.932 --> 00:35:58.890
But we lure them into a
false sense of security

00:35:58.890 --> 00:36:00.598
first by having them
just straight lines,

00:36:00.598 --> 00:36:02.280
and then we add
the triangle later.

00:36:02.280 --> 00:36:05.250
And they're like, oh, no.

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:06.660
They'll be OK, though.

00:36:06.660 --> 00:36:08.340
The first thing we
do is differentiate

00:36:08.340 --> 00:36:10.987
sexuality from sexual
orientation because, of course,

00:36:10.987 --> 00:36:11.820
these are different.

00:36:11.820 --> 00:36:13.754
But people use them
interchangeably a lot.

00:36:13.754 --> 00:36:15.420
The reason we like
to differentiate them

00:36:15.420 --> 00:36:17.600
is that we're not talking
about sexuality in schools.

00:36:17.600 --> 00:36:18.391
It doesn't come up.

00:36:18.391 --> 00:36:19.910
It doesn't happen.

00:36:19.910 --> 00:36:22.480
And people use it to deny
our access in schools.

00:36:22.480 --> 00:36:24.790
They say, I don't
just don't think

00:36:24.790 --> 00:36:27.320
you should be talking
about sexuality in schools.

00:36:27.320 --> 00:36:29.040
What does that possibly
got to do-- this

00:36:29.040 --> 00:36:30.210
is every mother's accent.

00:36:30.210 --> 00:36:33.690
What does that possibly
got to do with school?

00:36:33.690 --> 00:36:36.840
And they're there
to learn and blah.

00:36:36.840 --> 00:36:38.760
So we say, well,
we're not doing that,

00:36:38.760 --> 00:36:41.051
because sexuality is different
than sexual orientation.

00:36:41.051 --> 00:36:44.580
Sexuality is how much you like
sex, the type of sex you like,

00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:46.360
the frequency of the sex.

00:36:46.360 --> 00:36:48.090
Sexual orientation
is with whom you

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:49.742
might want to have that sex.

00:36:49.742 --> 00:36:51.200
So when we talk to
young people, we

00:36:51.200 --> 00:36:53.366
talk about sexual orientation--
more often than not,

00:36:53.366 --> 00:36:55.010
romantic orientation.

00:36:55.010 --> 00:36:57.360
We don't talk about sexuality.

00:36:57.360 --> 00:36:59.610
We do in the corporates, if
you ever want to book one,

00:36:59.610 --> 00:37:01.610
talk about sexuality.

00:37:01.610 --> 00:37:03.890
But I guess the important
point around sexuality

00:37:03.890 --> 00:37:06.420
is just how much we
moralize sex, right?

00:37:06.420 --> 00:37:08.900
So asexual people--
they get extremely

00:37:08.900 --> 00:37:11.120
discriminated against,
saying, you don't have sex?

00:37:11.120 --> 00:37:12.230
You're weird then.

00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:14.019
Or you haven't met
the right person.

00:37:14.019 --> 00:37:15.060
You don't know your body.

00:37:15.060 --> 00:37:16.726
Or you're not being
sex positive enough.

00:37:16.726 --> 00:37:19.092
All this really annoying
rhetoric for them,

00:37:19.092 --> 00:37:20.550
which denies them
their right to be

00:37:20.550 --> 00:37:25.480
in charge of their own
label, rule number one.

00:37:25.480 --> 00:37:29.130
So you can consider
sex positivity

00:37:29.130 --> 00:37:30.722
to be a movement
that is about being

00:37:30.722 --> 00:37:32.430
comfortable with any
amount of sex you're

00:37:32.430 --> 00:37:34.102
having because no one is.

00:37:34.102 --> 00:37:36.060
There's too little sex,
and you should feel bad

00:37:36.060 --> 00:37:37.518
about that, because
you're a loser.

00:37:37.518 --> 00:37:38.790
You're not having sex.

00:37:38.790 --> 00:37:39.850
And there's too much sex.

00:37:39.850 --> 00:37:41.280
You should feel bad
about that because you're

00:37:41.280 --> 00:37:42.600
a little slut, right?

00:37:42.600 --> 00:37:45.000
And then there's this
perfect amount of sex

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.250
that you can feel good
about having, and no one

00:37:47.250 --> 00:37:48.420
knows what it is.

00:37:48.420 --> 00:37:50.850
So we all just feel
bad all of the time.

00:37:50.850 --> 00:37:53.250
Welcome to Ireland.

00:37:53.250 --> 00:37:55.110
So we like to talk
about this a little bit

00:37:55.110 --> 00:37:57.330
and get people to realize
that, as long as you're

00:37:57.330 --> 00:37:59.820
comfortable and
consensual and happy,

00:37:59.820 --> 00:38:01.620
and that's all that matters.

00:38:01.620 --> 00:38:04.470
And there's a couple of ways
you can talk about these issues.

00:38:04.470 --> 00:38:08.160
You can build on ideas that
people already have, build it

00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:12.240
up, blocky blocky, or you
can flip the idea on its head

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:16.350
and go with the most complicated
issue first and build down.

00:38:16.350 --> 00:38:20.820
And this is where we have our
pyramid of queer concepts.

00:38:20.820 --> 00:38:23.520
So at the bottom, love is love.

00:38:23.520 --> 00:38:24.960
Isn't love grand?

00:38:24.960 --> 00:38:26.640
Love knows no gender.

00:38:26.640 --> 00:38:27.990
Love is love.

00:38:27.990 --> 00:38:29.010
Everyone knows this.

00:38:29.010 --> 00:38:30.300
Most people accept this.

00:38:30.300 --> 00:38:32.160
If people don't
accept this, they're

00:38:32.160 --> 00:38:34.285
not really going to get on
board with a lot of what

00:38:34.285 --> 00:38:35.480
I'm saying anyway.

00:38:35.480 --> 00:38:37.230
I don't know why they
came to my workshop.

00:38:37.230 --> 00:38:39.450
So yeah, love is love.

00:38:39.450 --> 00:38:41.610
Tout it around a lot.

00:38:41.610 --> 00:38:45.360
I absolutely despise it,
but that's another workshop.

00:38:45.360 --> 00:38:46.075
Love is not love.

00:38:46.075 --> 00:38:47.700
People are people,
and love isn't love.

00:38:47.700 --> 00:38:51.079
That's their takeaway
message from this talk.

00:38:51.079 --> 00:38:52.620
But it's a really
good place to start

00:38:52.620 --> 00:38:57.610
because people, in general,
accept that love is love

00:38:57.610 --> 00:39:00.030
and that love is grand.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:00.657
You do you.

00:39:00.657 --> 00:39:03.240
That is my general way of saying
people can express themselves

00:39:03.240 --> 00:39:05.100
however they like.

00:39:05.100 --> 00:39:07.170
Men can wear nail varnish-- ooh.

00:39:07.170 --> 00:39:08.340
Women can be butch--

00:39:08.340 --> 00:39:09.490
that type of thing.

00:39:09.490 --> 00:39:12.602
A little less people
accept that, but more

00:39:12.602 --> 00:39:14.310
than the next thing,
which is everyone is

00:39:14.310 --> 00:39:15.750
in charge of their own label.

00:39:15.750 --> 00:39:16.860
People don't like that.

00:39:16.860 --> 00:39:18.270
People love gatekeeping.

00:39:18.270 --> 00:39:18.960
They love it.

00:39:18.960 --> 00:39:21.210
It's their favorite thing.

00:39:21.210 --> 00:39:23.340
So if you, say,
had a gay man who

00:39:23.340 --> 00:39:27.310
sleeps with multiple genders,
sleeps with women very often,

00:39:27.310 --> 00:39:29.310
people would love to deny
them that they're gay.

00:39:29.310 --> 00:39:31.140
But they're in charge
of their own label.

00:39:31.140 --> 00:39:33.750
Now, are they not using
the label bisexual because

00:39:33.750 --> 00:39:35.740
of the stigma around
being bisexual?

00:39:35.740 --> 00:39:36.240
Maybe.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:37.110
Probably.

00:39:37.110 --> 00:39:38.250
Let's work on that stigma.

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:40.080
Let's not chastise the
person for the label they've

00:39:40.080 --> 00:39:40.680
chosen, OK?

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:42.500
Everyone's in charge
of their own label.

00:39:42.500 --> 00:39:46.290
We get people to accept that,
then they have less of a

00:39:46.290 --> 00:39:49.480
back and forth about, but
if you're this, and then

00:39:49.480 --> 00:39:51.150
how can you be that if--

00:39:51.150 --> 00:39:54.610
and we're like, well, everyone's
in charge of their own label.

00:39:54.610 --> 00:39:56.350
Sex isn't the same as gender.

00:39:56.350 --> 00:39:58.630
Way less acceptance
around this because we

00:39:58.630 --> 00:40:00.370
like to interchange--

00:40:00.370 --> 00:40:01.810
twist it all up a lot.

00:40:01.810 --> 00:40:05.080
But when you kind of get into
the concepts and the idea

00:40:05.080 --> 00:40:07.720
that there's always been
third genders in society

00:40:07.720 --> 00:40:11.401
since record in every
anthropological study ever.

00:40:11.401 --> 00:40:13.900
Every society has found third
genders-- that's male, female,

00:40:13.900 --> 00:40:15.702
and third genders.

00:40:15.702 --> 00:40:18.160
In Native American culture,
it's called being two-spirited.

00:40:18.160 --> 00:40:20.160
In Southeast Asia, it's
called being hijra.

00:40:20.160 --> 00:40:21.794
The Maori have
their own version.

00:40:21.794 --> 00:40:23.710
That's been around for
a very, very long time,

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:25.630
and that is not
connected to sex--

00:40:25.630 --> 00:40:28.935
sex being a set of
biological traits.

00:40:28.935 --> 00:40:30.310
So when people
don't accept this,

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:31.900
they're being bioessentialist.

00:40:31.900 --> 00:40:34.990
But you can get a
lot of people there.

00:40:34.990 --> 00:40:36.760
Gender isn't binary.

00:40:36.760 --> 00:40:38.770
That's a little bit
trickier because we've

00:40:38.770 --> 00:40:40.690
been touting this--
men and women, the men

00:40:40.690 --> 00:40:42.170
and women of this country.

00:40:42.170 --> 00:40:44.390
And all the forms
say male and female.

00:40:44.390 --> 00:40:45.880
There is no other option.

00:40:45.880 --> 00:40:49.510
There might be
options on cool forms,

00:40:49.510 --> 00:40:52.990
but not government forms.

00:40:52.990 --> 00:40:56.240
Eventually, you might get
people to accept down in the

00:40:56.240 --> 00:40:57.490
"you do you."

00:40:57.490 --> 00:40:59.977
You kind of bring that up
and say, well, ultimately,

00:40:59.977 --> 00:41:01.310
what does it take away from you?

00:41:01.310 --> 00:41:03.700
And if you have to
go down that route,

00:41:03.700 --> 00:41:06.310
it's not ideal,
because we are trying

00:41:06.310 --> 00:41:09.460
to aim a little bit higher
than tolerance-- trying to aim

00:41:09.460 --> 00:41:11.720
for acceptance and celebration.

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:13.720
But sometimes, you have
to settle for tolerance.

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:15.400
You can't do this
and be a purist.

00:41:15.400 --> 00:41:17.030
It just wouldn't work.

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:22.480
So you have to put all
your woke ideals aside

00:41:22.480 --> 00:41:25.494
because you have
to bridge that gap.

00:41:25.494 --> 00:41:26.660
And that's what we're doing.

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:28.576
We are standing in between
the two communities

00:41:28.576 --> 00:41:30.880
and bridging the
gap as best we can.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:34.090
And then either is sex--
that's the toughest one.

00:41:34.090 --> 00:41:35.740
Sex isn't binary, either.

00:41:35.740 --> 00:41:38.290
There's all these other
traits you can have.

00:41:38.290 --> 00:41:40.240
There's different
ways to be a person.

00:41:40.240 --> 00:41:42.060
You can have
ambiguous genitalia.

00:41:42.060 --> 00:41:43.840
That's a terrible
term, but it's what is

00:41:43.840 --> 00:41:45.910
used in the medical industry.

00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:49.032
You can have XY chromosomes
normally, typically

00:41:49.032 --> 00:41:51.490
associated with being male,
but you can have XY chromosomes

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:52.687
and have a vagina.

00:41:52.687 --> 00:41:53.395
And this happens.

00:41:53.395 --> 00:41:54.900
It's not something I've made up.

00:41:54.900 --> 00:41:57.830
And in that case, is that
person male or female?

00:41:57.830 --> 00:41:58.930
We don't know.

00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:00.140
What is being male or female?

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:00.970
We don't know.

00:42:00.970 --> 00:42:04.780
It's all a series of
spectrums and different ways

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:05.840
of looking at things.

00:42:05.840 --> 00:42:08.830
We like to think about
it as very, very strict.

00:42:08.830 --> 00:42:11.770
And that's because
it's easy to teach kids

00:42:11.770 --> 00:42:14.920
about strict ideas that
fall into certain boxes.

00:42:14.920 --> 00:42:16.750
That is an easy way
to think about things.

00:42:16.750 --> 00:42:18.970
But if you study biology
at a higher level,

00:42:18.970 --> 00:42:21.070
you realize that most of
biology is people being

00:42:21.070 --> 00:42:25.044
like, [MUMBLES], I don't know.

00:42:25.044 --> 00:42:26.360
It's all very weird.

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:29.220
I don't know.

00:42:29.220 --> 00:42:32.020
And that's very confronting
for people to not feel

00:42:32.020 --> 00:42:34.780
like they know the truth and
that they've been lied to.

00:42:34.780 --> 00:42:36.487
And you haven't
lied to every time

00:42:36.487 --> 00:42:38.320
you've been told there's
only men and women.

00:42:38.320 --> 00:42:39.130
You haven't been lied to.

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:41.046
You just haven't been
told the full truth, OK?

00:42:41.046 --> 00:42:41.980
And that's OK.

00:42:41.980 --> 00:42:44.440
So you can either build up, or
you can flip it on its head,

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:47.080
start with the fact the
biological sex is not binary,

00:42:47.080 --> 00:42:47.890
and move downwards.

00:42:47.890 --> 00:42:50.740
Because if biological sex
isn't binary, what is gender?

00:42:50.740 --> 00:42:51.400
What is sex?

00:42:51.400 --> 00:42:52.930
Who does it care
who you love, yeah?

00:42:52.930 --> 00:42:53.916
You can go that way.

00:42:53.916 --> 00:42:55.040
So it's one way or another.

00:42:55.040 --> 00:42:57.700
And it's all about the
audience that you're with,

00:42:57.700 --> 00:43:00.310
the type of people they are,
and the tactic you think

00:43:00.310 --> 00:43:01.780
is going to work on the day.

00:43:01.780 --> 00:43:04.240
So you decide at the time.

00:43:04.240 --> 00:43:08.230
So I'm very uncomfortable
that you know all my secrets.

00:43:08.230 --> 00:43:12.590
Now, I would like to ask
if you have any queries.

00:43:12.590 --> 00:43:13.090
Thank you.

00:43:13.090 --> 00:43:16.583
